that there is so little water at home. This is despite the fact that I grew up at Sena City, where there is more than enough water. Furthermore, we have driers here, despite the entity that managed the water sanitation throwing thousands of liters of water in the comb what is a shame and lack of critical empathy to our fellow citizens who are very poor.

Although the water problem affects all of us, a huge issue with city halls supervision of those driers situated inTownside, is that the privatized services are not operating at full capacity, in line with the key component of their contracts. In the middle of a serious water crisis the businesses charge me more than 100W for every 4 liters of water. Last week a 20 1/2 litre bucket cost me 1000 meticais. A really good price, setting aside the fact that this is the worse water that I have drunk in my entire life. Curiously, in downtown in Maputo lies a water company owned by the City Hall, and this is privatized by Amatola Company. But again, Sena City is much better serviced than City Centre!

As you can see, the very existence of another entity, which should exist because here no one has the time to go to City Centre more than once a month, is a clear evidence that elected officials, who have profited from their positions, are not streamlining these issues, despite everything that has already been said for years.
